  		<div><h3>Comments</h3></div>
  		<div>
  			<div id="item-3494"><p>this sounds so delicious. i&#8217;ve always wanted to make my own pot pie. how essential are the cranberries? just because I think i have all the ingredients besides the berries and wonder if i could just go ahead without them&#8230;</p></div>
  			<div class="date byline">
  				
  				<span><span class="alias">jeannie</span></span>
  				<span>on March 7, 2007</span>
  			</div>
  		</div><div>
  			<div id="item-3495"><p>You can put anything you want in the pie, some recipes call for sliced celery and/or tiny onions. Just remember that vegetables like that need to be cooked first. Frozen vegetables generally just need to be thawed. The cranberries are strictly my own whimsical addition; I like the contrast of flavor, color, and hint of Thanksgiving they provide.</p></div>
  			<div class="date byline">
  				
  				<span><span class="alias">Rebecca (Mommy)</span></span>
  				<span>on March 7, 2007</span>
  			</div>
  		</div><div>
  			<div id="item-3496"><p>That looks delicious&#8230; I&#8217;m really hungry now! :)</p>
<p>If I were to make that, I would have to omit the carrots because I&#8217;m quite allergic to them.  Could you suggest something as a replacement?</p></div>
  			<div class="date byline">
  				
  				<a href="http://colinwetherbee.com/"><span class="alias">Colin</span></a>
  				<span>on March 7, 2007</span>
  			</div>
  		</div><div>
  			<div id="item-3497"><p>I have never heard of vinegar in pie crust and have never seen such long instructions to make a pie crust, but I must admit, my curiosity is peaked. I love pot pies.</p></div>
  			<div class="date byline">
  				
  				<span><span class="alias">jancd</span></span>
  				<span>on March 7, 2007</span>
  			</div>
  		</div><div>
  			<div id="item-3498"><p>Colin, you could try substituting cubed sweet potatoes or one of the winter squashes since I think they would replace carrots in sweetness and color. You might want to omit the regular potatoes in that case because the whole thing would start to get too starchy, and just increase the amounts of the other vegetables.</p>
<p>Jan, I think the vinegar makes the crust tender or something, but I should have said any pie pastry can be used here. My instructions are long because I was gearing the pastry recipe toward first-time pastry-makers.</p></div>
  			<div class="date byline">
  				
  				<span><span class="alias">Rebecca (Mommy)</span></span>
  				<span>on March 7, 2007</span>
  			</div>
  		</div><div>
  			<div id="item-3499"><p>I love the double crust too! The pie looks delicious!</p></div>
  			<div class="date byline">
  				
  				<a href="http://zombiesnack.blogspot.com"><span class="alias">Freya</span></a>
  				<span>on March 7, 2007</span>
  			</div>
  		</div><div>
  			<div id="item-3500"><p>Oh, this looks wonderful.. I have such a time with pot pies.. Sometimes the liquid consistency is too much. Other times, it&#8217;s nonexistant. I can never get it just right..</p></div>
  			<div class="date byline">
  				
  				<a href="http://madisonandmayberry.typepad.com"><span class="alias">Andrea</span></a>
  				<span>on March 7, 2007</span>
  			</div>
  		</div><div>
  			<div id="item-3501"><p>Hi, Andrea! My preference is always for more sauce rather than less, especially if you use a double crust. If you make too much, add it until it looks nice and saucy, then just save the rest and use it as a sauce for broccoli or asparagus the next night; I actually had about 1/2 cup I didn&#8217;t use last night.</p></div>
  			<div class="date byline">
  				
  				<span><span class="alias">Rebecca (Mommy)</span></span>
  				<span>on March 7, 2007</span>
  			</div>
  		</div><div>
  			<div id="item-3502"><p>Potpies are gorgeous, and this one is brilliant. I do think M. Cunningham is a genius at American food.</p></div>
  			<div class="date byline">
  				
  				<a href="http://lindystoast.com"><span class="alias">lindy</span></a>
  				<span>on March 7, 2007</span>
  			</div>
  		</div><div>
  			<div id="item-3503"><p>I&#8217;ve never made a chicken pot pie. It always seems sort of daunting. You make it sound so easy though.</p></div>
  			<div class="date byline">
  				
  				<a href="http://kitchenography.typepad.com"><span class="alias">Julie</span></a>
  				<span>on March 7, 2007</span>
  			</div>
  		</div><div>
  			<div id="item-3504"><p>Lindy&#8212;Don&#8217;t you love those little breakfast and supper books she put out? I have gotten a lot of recipes out of the supper book.</p>
<p>Julie&#8212;None of the steps are hard but there are a lot of them. You can simplify a little by using a biscuit topping, or even easier with store-bought puff pastry, both of which are still delicious. And backing up, you can add a step by poaching your own chicken, which I often do.</p></div>
  			<div class="date byline">
  				
  				<span><span class="alias">Rebecca</span></span>
  				<span>on March 7, 2007</span>
